result.execSummary:
The defendant Lateciah M. Wanserski was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Unlawful Phone Use-Threaten w/ Obscenity, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.012(1)(b).
  • Unlawful Phone Use-Threaten w/ Obscenity [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.012(1)(b).
  • Unlawful Phone Use-Threatens Harm, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.012(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Letter from Atty Renc dated 12/11/14 with attached documents

Defendant Lateciah M. Wanserski in court with attorney Jared Redfield. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

State files Amended Information.
Plea questionnaire/Agreement filed.
Prosecutor states plea agreement.
Attorney for Defendant concurs with agreement stated.

Defendant received the amended information.
Defendant questions the Domestic Abuse charge and how it will affect her schooling. 
Atty Redfield makes statements. 
Atty Knaapen makes statements. 
Atty Redfield makes statements requesting expungment. 
Atty Knaapen makes statements as to the reduction of the charges to 3 misdemeanors for repeater status. 
Defendant indicates she would like to proceed today.  
State files Victim Impact Statements.  As well as a letter from Atty Renc that was addressed to Judge Flugaur. 

Atty Redfield enters a plea of:  Counts 1, 2 & 3 -  NO CONTEST on defendant's behalf at her request. 

Court questions Defendant regarding plea.
Court informs Defendant of Constitutional Rights. Court advises Defendant of Elements State must prove for the Charge.
Court questions Attorney for Defendant.
Court finds Defendant's Plea is freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.
Attorneys stipulate that there is factual basis for the charge(s).

BY THE COURT:
Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charge(s).
Court finds the defendant guilty on counts 1, 2 & 3.  Clerk directed to enter Judgment of Conviction this date.

Defendant makes statements to the Court. 
Atty Redfield makes statements to the Court.  Requests expungment. 
BY THE COURT:  Motion to expunge is denied. 

BY THE COURT: 
Sentence withheld 
Placed on probation for a period of 24 months on each count:
Undertake mental health counseling as the agent reasonably requires. 
Undertake such other counseling that is reasonably required by the agent. 
Pay costs on each count. 
Count 2 does carry the domestic abuse surcharge. 
Comply with the injunction in 13CV265 for as long as that injunction remains in place or until 24 months has gone by. 

Court advises Atty Redfield to review the appellate rights with his client.
Plea/sentencing hearing on December 16, 2014 at 02:00 pm.
Pre-trial conference on July 28, 2014 at 10:30 am.

Defendant waives right to preliminary hearing. 
Court questions defendant regarding waiver of preliminary hearing. 
Court questions Attorney.
Court finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived the preliminary hearing. 
On the defendants waiver of the preliminary hearing, Court determines, based on the facts contained in the complaint, there is sufficient probable cause and binds the defendant over for trial. 

State files Information.
Defendant received copy of information.
Defendant waives reading of information. 

NOT GUILTY Pleas entered.

Bond Continued.

No contact with Max Alvarez other than those provisions describe with visitation of common child or other emergency responses involving that child if necessary. 
No contact with Alexandria Salzer or the residence of Max Alvarez and Alexandria Salzer.

Defendant Lateciah M. Wanserski in court with attorney Jared C Redfield. David R Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Attorney/Defendant received copy of criminal complaint.
Court informs defendant of charges and maximum penalties.
Court reads complaint for the defendant. 

Atty Knaapen requests a $5,000 signature bond with conditions as stated. 
Atty Redfield makes bond arguments with regards to the no contact request.
Atty Knaapen makes statements regarding civil injunction. 
Defendant makes statemetns. 
Court questions defendant further.
  Attorney waives time limits for preliminary hearing to be held.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for July 28, 2014 at 10:30 am.
Initial appearance on June 9, 2014 at 01:30 pm.
